<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ws-vectors.ptx
    Worksheet 1.2: Vectors.

    Ports the original 01_01_Vectors.tex slide deck.  Same five-part
    organization as the Beamer notes:
        I.   Vector basics (notation, components, basis vectors, equality)
        II.  Vector addition (and "resultant" terminology)
        III. Scalar multiplication
        IV.  Length / norm / unit vectors
        V.   Application: resultant force and equilibrium

    Guided-notes pattern (see ws-function-notation.ptx for full
    explanation):
        - <fillin characters="N"/> draws a blank in BOTH builds.
        - The matching answer follows in a <commentary> block,
          which appears only on the instructor build (per the
          'commentary' stringparam in project.ptx).
        - Multi-step worked computations are <exercise>s with a
          <solution> body whose visibility is controlled by the
          <exercise-worksheet @solution="..."/> entry in the
          publication file.

    Figures (parallelogram rule, scalar-multiple stretching) are
    left as <figure> placeholders so the existing PNGs from the
    LaTeX source can be dropped in later.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-vectors">
    <title>Vectors</title>

    <objectives>
        <ul>
            <li>Read and write vectors in <m>\R^2</m> and <m>\R^3</m>
                in both bracket and <m>\vi,\vj,\vk</m> form.</li>
            <li>Test two vectors for equality and use equality to
                solve for unknown components.</li>
            <li>Add vectors and multiply vectors by scalars, both
                algebraically and geometrically.</li>
            <li>Compute the length (norm) of a vector and produce a
                unit vector in a prescribed direction.</li>
            <li>Apply vector addition to find a resultant force and
                test a system of forces for equilibrium.</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 1: Vector basics, notation, equality
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>I. Vector basics.</alert></p>

        <definition xml:id="def-vector">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A <term>vector</term> <m>\vv</m> is a
                    mathematical object that has both
                    <fillin characters="20"/>
                    <nbsp/>and <fillin characters="12"/>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order: <q>magnitude</q> (or
                <q>length</q>) and <q>direction</q>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <p><alert>Notation conventions used in this course.</alert></p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                A vector is written in <term>bold</term> or with an
                <term>arrow</term>: <m>\vv</m>, <m>\vec{v}</m>.  In
                handwriting we'll use the arrow.
            </li>
            <li>
                A vector <m>\vv</m> in <m>\R^2</m> is described by
                <fillin characters="3"/> <nbsp/>coordinates:
                <m>\vv = </m> <fillin characters="10"/>
                <m>\in \R^2</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
                A vector <m>\vv</m> in <m>\R^3</m> is described by
                <fillin characters="3"/> <nbsp/>coordinates:
                <m>\vv = </m> <fillin characters="14"/>
                <m>\in \R^3</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
                The <term>standard basis vectors</term>
                <me>
                    \vi = [1,0,0], \quad
                    \vj = [0,1,0], \quad
                    \vk = [0,0,1]
                </me>
                let us rewrite any vector as a linear combination:
                <me>
                    \vv = [v_1, v_2, v_3] = \fillin[24]
                </me>
            </li>
        </ul>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order: <q>2</q>, <m>[v_1,\,v_2]</m>,
                <q>3</q>, <m>[v_1,\,v_2,\,v_3]</m>, and
                <m>v_1\,\vi + v_2\,\vj + v_3\,\vk</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <example xml:id="ex-vector-examples">
            <title>Reading vectors</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Classify each vector and rewrite it in
                    <m>\vi,\vj,\vk</m> form when possible.</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><m>[10, 14]</m>, <m>[0, 1]</m>,
                        <m>[-1, 2]</m> are in
                        <fillin characters="4"/>, and
                        <m>[10, 4] = </m> <fillin characters="16"/>.</li>
                    <li><m>[1, 1, -1]</m>, <m>[0, 0, 0]</m>,
                        <m>[-10, 12, -8]</m> are in
                        <fillin characters="4"/>, and
                        <me>
                            [-10, 12, -8] = \fillin[28]
                        </me>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
        </example>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Part (1) blanks: <m>\R^2</m> and
                <m>10\,\vi + 4\,\vj</m>.  Part (2) blanks:
                <m>\R^3</m> and
                <m>-10\,\vi + 12\,\vj - 8\,\vk</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <theorem xml:id="thm-vector-equality">
            <title>Vector equality</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\va = [a_1, a_2, a_3]</m> and
                    <m>\vb = [b_1, b_2, b_3]</m>.  Then
                    <m>\va = \vb</m> if and only if
                    <fillin characters="40"/>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </theorem>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Fill in:
                <m>a_1 = b_1</m>, <m>a_2 = b_2</m>, and
                <m>a_3 = b_3</m> &#8212; the components match
                one-by-one.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-equality">
            <title>Using vector equality</title>
            <task xml:id="task-eq-a">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find <m>c</m> and <m>d</m> so that
                        <me>
                            [2,\; 0,\; 2d+c] = [c,\; 0,\; 1].
                        </me>
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Matching components gives <m>c = 2</m> and
                        <m>2d + c = 1</m>.  Substituting,
                        <m>2d + 2 = 1</m>, so
                        <m>d = -\tfrac{1}{2}</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-eq-b">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find all <m>s, t</m> so that
                        <m>[s^2,\; t] = [4,\; s + t]</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        From the first component, <m>s = \pm 2</m>.
                        From the second, <m>t = s + t</m> gives
                        <m>s = 0</m> &#8212; which contradicts
                        <m>s = \pm 2</m>.  So no solution exists.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </page>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 2: Vector addition (and "resultant")
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>II. Vector addition.</alert>
            (Vector Operation #1)</p>

        <p>
            Let <m>\va = [a_1, a_2, a_3]</m> and
            <m>\vb = [b_1, b_2, b_3]</m>.  Then
            <me>
                \va + \vb
                = [a_1, a_2, a_3] + [b_1, b_2, b_3]
                = \fillin[34]
            </me>
            Vector addition is just <em>componentwise</em> addition.
        </p>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Fill in:
                <m>[a_1 + b_1,\; a_2 + b_2,\; a_3 + b_3]</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <figure xml:id="fig-vector-addition">
            <caption>Vector addition by the parallelogram (or
                head-to-tail) rule.</caption>
            <!-- TODO: drop in the existing 9_1_Fig1/2/3 PNGs, e.g.
                 <image source="figures/vec-add-parallelogram.png"
                        width="60%"/>
                 or replace with an inline TikZ <latex-image>. -->
            <image>
                <description>Two vectors a and b drawn tail-to-tail
                    from a common origin, completed into a
                    parallelogram whose diagonal from the origin is
                    the sum a + b.</description>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p><alert>Notes.</alert></p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                If <m>\va, \vb \in \R^3</m> then
                <m>\va + \vb \in</m> <fillin characters="6"/>.
                Adding vectors of the same dimension produces a
                vector of the same dimension.
            </li>
            <li>
                The sum <m>\va + \vb</m> is called the
                <term>resultant</term> of <m>\va</m> and
                <m>\vb</m>.  If <m>\va</m> and <m>\vb</m> are
                forces, then <m>\va + \vb</m> is the
                <fillin characters="18"/>.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order: <m>\R^3</m>, and
                <q>resultant force</q>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-add">
            <title>Adding two vectors</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\va = [1, -3, 2]</m> and
                    <m>\vb = [4, 0, -1]</m>.  Compute
                    <m>\va + \vb</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \va + \vb
                            \amp = [1 + 4,\; -3 + 0,\; 2 + (-1)] </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = [5,\; -3,\; 1].              </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-add">
            <title>Addition practice</title>
            <task xml:id="task-add-a">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        With <m>\va = [2, 5]</m> and
                        <m>\vb = [-3, 4]</m>, compute
                        <m>\va + \vb</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\va + \vb = [2 + (-3),\; 5 + 4]
                        = [-1,\; 9]</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-add-b">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        With <m>\vu = 3\vi - \vj + 2\vk</m> and
                        <m>\vv = -\vi + 4\vj + \vk</m>, compute
                        <m>\vu + \vv</m> in <m>\vi,\vj,\vk</m> form.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\vu + \vv = (3-1)\vi + (-1+4)\vj
                        + (2+1)\vk = 2\vi + 3\vj + 3\vk</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </page>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 3: Scalar multiplication
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>III. Scalar multiplication.</alert></p>

        <p>
            Let <m>\vv = [v_1, v_2, v_3] \in \R^3</m> and let
            <m>c \in \R</m> be a scalar.  Then
            <me>
                c\,\vv = c\,[v_1, v_2, v_3] = \fillin[24]
            </me>
            Scalar multiplication is componentwise.
        </p>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Fill in:
                <m>[c\,v_1,\; c\,v_2,\; c\,v_3]</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <figure xml:id="fig-scalar-multiplication">
            <caption>Scalar multiples of a vector.</caption>
            <!-- TODO: drop in 9_1_Fig4. -->
            <image>
                <description>The vector v, together with 2v (longer,
                    same direction), 0.5v (shorter, same direction),
                    and -v (same length, opposite direction).</description>
            </image>
        </figure>

        <p><alert>Notes.</alert></p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Scalar multiplication can <fillin characters="10"/>
                <nbsp/>(when <m>\norm{c} > 1</m>),
                <fillin characters="10"/>
                <nbsp/>(when <m>0 &lt; \norm{c} &lt; 1</m>), or
                <fillin characters="6"/> <nbsp/>(when
                <m>c &lt; 0</m>) a vector.
            </li>
            <li>
                The dimension is unchanged: <m>\vv \in \R^n</m>
                and <m>c \in \R</m> give <m>c\vv \in</m>
                <fillin characters="6"/>.
            </li>
        </ul>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Blanks, in order: <q>stretch</q>,
                <q>compress</q>, <q>flip</q>, and <m>\R^n</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-scalar-mult">
            <title>A scalar multiple</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\vv = [2, -1, 4]</m> and <m>c = -3</m>.
                    Compute <m>c\,\vv</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>c\,\vv = -3\,[2, -1, 4]
                    = [-6,\; 3,\; -12]</m>.  The result has the
                    same direction line as <m>\vv</m> but points
                    the opposite way and is three times as long.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-scalar-mult">
            <title>Combining the two operations</title>
            <task xml:id="task-sm-a">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        With <m>\va = [1, 2, -1]</m> and
                        <m>\vb = [3, 0, 4]</m>, compute
                        <m>2\,\va - 3\,\vb</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <md>
                            <mrow>
                                2\,\va - 3\,\vb
                                \amp = [2, 4, -2] - [9, 0, 12]    </mrow>
                            <mrow>
                                \amp = [2-9,\; 4-0,\; -2-12]      </mrow>
                            <mrow>
                                \amp = [-7,\; 4,\; -14].          </mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-sm-b">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find a scalar <m>c</m> so that
                        <m>c\,[3, -6, 9] = [1, -2, 3]</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>c = \tfrac{1}{3}</m>; each component of
                        the right-hand side is one-third of the
                        corresponding component on the left.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </page>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 4: Length / norm and unit vectors
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>IV. Length (norm) of a vector.</alert></p>

        <definition xml:id="def-norm">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>\vv = [v_1, v_2] \in \R^2</m> and
                    <m>\vw = [w_1, w_2, w_3] \in \R^3</m>.  The
                    <term>length</term> (or <term>norm</term>) of
                    each, denoted <m>\norm{\vv}</m> and
                    <m>\norm{\vw}</m>, is
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \norm{\vv} \amp = \fillin[24] </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \norm{\vw} \amp = \fillin[32] </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Fill in:
                <m>\norm{\vv} = \sqrt{v_1^2 + v_2^2}</m> and
                <m>\norm{\vw} = \sqrt{w_1^2 + w_2^2 + w_3^2}</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-length">
            <title>Computing a length</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the length of <m>\vw = [1, -2, 4]</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \norm{\vw}
                            \amp = \sqrt{(1)^2 + (-2)^2 + (4)^2} </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = \sqrt{1 + 4 + 16}             </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                            \amp = \sqrt{21}.                    </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <p><alert>Note.</alert>
            <m>\vw \in \R^3</m> is a <em>vector</em>, but its length
            <m>\norm{\vw} \in</m> <fillin characters="14"/>.
            Length is a single non-negative real number.
        </p>
        <commentary>
            <p>Fill in: <m>\R</m> (a scalar).</p>
        </commentary>

        <definition xml:id="def-unit-vector">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A vector <m>\vv</m> is a <term>unit
                    vector</term> if <fillin characters="14"/>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <commentary>
            <p>Fill in: <m>\norm{\vv} = 1</m>.</p>
        </commentary>

        <p>
            <alert>Producing a unit vector.</alert>
            Given any non-zero vector <m>\vw</m>, the vector
            <me>
                \vu = \fillin[18]
            </me>
            is a unit vector pointing in the same direction as
            <m>\vw</m>.  We sometimes say we have
            <term>normalized</term> the vector.
        </p>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Fill in: <m>\dfrac{\vw}{\norm{\vw}}</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-unit">
            <title>A unit vector in a given direction</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Find a unit vector <m>\vu</m> in the same
                    direction as <m>\vw = [1, -2, 4]</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    From the previous example,
                    <m>\norm{\vw} = \sqrt{21}</m>, so
                    <md>
                        <mrow>
                            \vu \amp = \frac{\vw}{\norm{\vw}}
                                  = \frac{1}{\sqrt{21}}[1,-2,4]   </mrow>
                        <mrow>
                                \amp = \left[
                                \frac{1}{\sqrt{21}},\;
                                \frac{-2}{\sqrt{21}},\;
                                \frac{4}{\sqrt{21}}
                                \right].                          </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Quick check:
                    <m>\norm{\vu}^2 = \tfrac{1 + 4 + 16}{21} = 1</m>,
                    so indeed <m>\norm{\vu} = 1</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-norm">
            <title>Norm and unit-vector practice</title>
            <task xml:id="task-norm-a">
                <statement>
                    <p>Find <m>\norm{\va}</m> for
                        <m>\va = [3, -4]</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\norm{\va} = \sqrt{9 + 16} = \sqrt{25}
                        = 5</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-norm-b">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find a unit vector in the direction of
                        <m>\vb = [2, 2, 1]</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\norm{\vb} = \sqrt{4 + 4 + 1} = 3</m>,
                        so <m>\vu = \tfrac{1}{3}[2,2,1]
                        = \left[\tfrac{2}{3},\, \tfrac{2}{3},\,
                                \tfrac{1}{3}\right]</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-norm-c">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Find a vector of length <m>10</m> in the
                        direction of <m>\vb = [2, 2, 1]</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        Scale the unit vector from part&#160;(b)
                        by <m>10</m>:
                        <m>10\,\vu
                        = \left[\tfrac{20}{3},\, \tfrac{20}{3},\,
                                \tfrac{10}{3}\right]</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>
    </page>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Page 5: Application - resultant force and equilibrium
         ============================================================ -->
    <page>
        <p><alert>V. Application: resultant force and
            equilibrium.</alert></p>

        <p>
            If forces <m>\vF_1, \vF_2, \ldots, \vF_n</m> act on a
            body, the <term>resultant force</term> on the body is
            their vector sum:
            <me>
                \vF = \fillin[18]
            </me>
        </p>
        <commentary>
            <p>
                Fill in:
                <m>\displaystyle\sum_{i=1}^{n} \vF_i</m>.
            </p>
        </commentary>

        <definition xml:id="def-equilibrium">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The forces <m>\vF_1, \vF_2, \ldots, \vF_n</m>
                    are in <term>equilibrium</term> if the resultant
                    is the zero vector: <fillin characters="14"/>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
        <commentary>
            <p>Fill in: <m>\vF = \vzero</m>.</p>
        </commentary>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-resultant">
            <title>A resultant force</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two forces act on an object,
                    <m>\vF_1 = [3,\,4]</m> and
                    <m>\vF_2 = [-1,\,2]</m> (in newtons).  Find the
                    resultant force and its magnitude.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The resultant is
                    <me>
                        \vF = \vF_1 + \vF_2
                            = [3 + (-1),\; 4 + 2]
                            = [2,\; 6].
                    </me>
                    Its magnitude is
                    <m>\norm{\vF} = \sqrt{2^2 + 6^2}
                    = \sqrt{40} = 2\sqrt{10}</m>
                    newtons.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exer-equilibrium">
            <title>Equilibrium</title>
            <task xml:id="task-eq-resultant-a">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        In the previous example, what third force
                        <m>\vF_3</m> would have to be applied so
                        that the three forces are in equilibrium?
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        We need <m>\vF_1 + \vF_2 + \vF_3 = \vzero</m>,
                        so <m>\vF_3 = -([2,6]) = [-2,\,-6]</m>
                        newtons.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-eq-resultant-b">
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Three forces act on a body:
                        <m>\vF_1 = [1, 0, 2]</m>,
                        <m>\vF_2 = [-3, 4, 1]</m>,
                        <m>\vF_3 = [2, -4, -3]</m>.  Is the body
                        in equilibrium?  If not, find the force
                        needed to put it in equilibrium.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\vF_1 + \vF_2 + \vF_3
                        = [1 - 3 + 2,\; 0 + 4 - 4,\; 2 + 1 - 3]
                        = [0, 0, 0] = \vzero</m>.  Yes, the body
                        <em>is</em> in equilibrium; no additional
                        force is needed.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </exercise>

        <p>
            <alert>Looking ahead.</alert>
            We've defined one vector operation (addition) and one
            way to combine a scalar with a vector.  The next
            worksheet introduces <em>two</em> ways to multiply two
            vectors together &#8212; the <term>dot product</term>
            (which produces a scalar) and the <term>cross
            product</term> (which produces a vector).
        </p>
    </page>

</worksheet>
